Defines the `ctx-verify` CLI surface: argv parsing via `clap` and rendering of a `Report` into either a terse human summary or the full JSON machine contract consumed by ctx-run/CI.

`Cli` fields drive scoping and output: `package` (cargo `-p` scope, whole-workspace if absent — module-level scoping doesn't exist at the cargo level), `max_diagnostics` (per-check cap, default 20), `checks` (comma-delimited allowlist restricting the default gate, empty = run everything), and `json` (switches to the machine format). `run<R: Runner, W: Write>(runner: &R, cli: &Cli, out: &mut W) -> Result<bool, CheckError>` is the entry point: builds the `only` filter from `cli.checks`, delegates to `checks::run_selected`, writes either JSON (via `serde_json::to_writer_pretty` plus a trailing newline) or the terse render, and returns whether `report.status == Status::Pass`. Errors are mapped to `CheckError::Encode`/`CheckError::Write` — this function never panics on a serialization or I/O failure.

The terse render (`render_terse`) is the load-bearing formatting logic: an all-pass report collapses to the single literal line `"pass"`; otherwise it emits one block per check whose status is neither `Pass` nor `Skipped` (skipped checks are silently omitted, not reported). Each block (`render_check`) is a `FAIL:`/`ERROR:` header with the check's diagnostic count, followed by diagnostics aligned to a common locator column width (computed per-check via `locs.iter().map(String::len).max()`), and a `… +N more` tail if `check.truncated > 0`. Diagnostic messages are clipped to `MAX_MSG = 100` chars with a trailing `…` (char-count based, not byte-based — `clip` uses `.chars()`). The locator (`locator`) degrades gracefully: `"-"` if no file, bare filename if no line number, `"file:line"` otherwise.

Coupling: the JSON branch is the wire contract other tools (ctx-run, CI) parse directly from `Report`/`CheckReport`/`Diagnostic` in `crate::model` — changing those structs' `Serialize` output changes this JSON without any change to this file. The terse format has no consumers besides human eyes, so its exact layout is free to change.